    "author_association": "CONTRIBUTOR",
    "body": "## Code Review\n\nReviewed test skip for Windows platform. The change adds a skip for the entire `TestGetModulesArchive` test on Windows due to path separator and newline handling issues.\n\n### Observations\n\n1. **Skip placement concern**: The skip is placed at the top level, which will skip ALL subtests (Success, EmptyDirectory, ModulesTooLarge, PackingPrioritizesSmallest, PackingAllFit, PackingNoneFit, PackingEdgeCaseExactFit, PackingMultipleSkipped). Only the \"Success\" subtest has platform-specific assertions and Windows-specific issues.\n\n2. **Existing platform handling**: The test already has conditional logic for Windows (lines 50-54 and 62-66), suggesting the test was designed to work cross-platform.\n\n### Recommendation\n\nConsider moving the skip to only the \"Success\" subtest instead of the entire test, since the other subtests use in-memory filesystems and don't depend on git line ending conversions or real filesystem behavior:\n\n```go\nt.Run(\"Success\", func(t *testing.T) {\n    t.Parallel()\n    if runtime.GOOS == \"windows\" {\n        t.Skip(\"Windows path separators and newline handling make this test unreliable.\")\n    }\n    // ... rest of test\n})\n```\n\nThis would preserve test coverage for the packing logic on Windows while skipping only the flaky filesystem-dependent test.\n\n### Verdict\n\nThe change is safe but potentially over-broad. If Windows flakiness is confirmed across all subtests, the current approach is fine. Otherwise, consider narrowing the skip scope.",
